docs.lead_paragraph: A survey of about two dozen programs found that average spending on food for Division I athletes had increased 145 percent since the N.C.A.A. lifted limitations on it in August 2014.

headline.main: Next Arms Race in Major Sports Is at the Food Table
headline.print_headline: A New Front in Competition: Cafeterias

docs.abstract: Ohio State has spent more than $1.5 million on its sports nutrition department in 2015; survey conducted by Collegiate and Professional Sports Dietitians Assn finds that top programs average spending on athletes’ diets increased 145 percent after NCAA lifted its limitations on meals and snacks for Division I athletes in 2014.
docs.snippet: A survey of about two dozen programs found that average spending on food for Division I athletes had increased 145 percent since the N.C.A.A. lifted limitations on it in August 2014.

docs.lead_paragraph: The University of Minnesota plans to break ground next month on its $166 million Athletes Village, which will include updated practice and training facilities for football and basketball teams that officials say are necessary to keep the school competitive in the Big Ten.

docs.lead_paragraph: Fire swept through a maximum-security Philippine prison killing 10 inmates, most of them in their cells, authorities said on Friday, in a disaster likely to highlight woeful conditions in one of the world's most over-crowded prison systems.
